# Table Explorer

The `tbl_explorer()` function generates an interactive table widget from tabular data. Where
[`tbl_preview()`](table-previews.qmd) produces a static, JavaScript-free snapshot of a dataset,
`tbl_explorer()` embeds all rows as inline JSON and progressively enhances a static fallback table
with interactive controls: sorting, token-based filtering, pagination, column toggling,
copy-to-clipboard, and CSV download.

Like `tbl_preview()`, `tbl_explorer()` accepts any tabular data source—Polars/Pandas DataFrames,
PyArrow Tables, CSV/TSV/JSONL/Parquet/Feather files, column-oriented dicts, or row-oriented lists of
dicts. The output is a self-contained HTML block that works in Python code cells, Jupyter notebooks,
and (via the `{{{< tbl-explorer >}}}` shortcode) directly in Quarto `.qmd` pages.

::: {.callout-note}
For datasets larger than 10,000 rows, `tbl_explorer()` emits a warning because all data is embedded
as JSON, which increases page weight. For very large datasets, consider using `tbl_preview()` with
`n_head`/`n_tail` splitting instead.
:::



## Basic Usage

Pass any supported data source to `tbl_explorer()` to get a fully interactive table:

::: {#6813f900 .cell execution_count=2}
``` {.python .cell-code}
from great_docs import tbl_explorer

tbl_explorer({
    "city": ["Tokyo", "Paris", "New York", "London", "Sydney"],
    "population": [13960000, 2161000, 8336000, 8982000, 5312000],
    "country": ["Japan", "France", "USA", "UK", "Australia"],
})
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=2}
